ive that reshaped postwar American culture: nonaesthetic mass culture reconceived and refashioned into rich, personally relevant art by the attuned, creative spectator.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCamp (Style). 0aFilm criticismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186276zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691186276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186276.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK